{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0179WQK7sZtRKrHU9hRfDq2P","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the current state. I need to deploy a 3-node Elasticsearch cluster using native Kubernetes resources (StatefulSet, Services, ConfigMap). Let me create the manifests.\n\nKey considerations:\n1. Use the existing TLS secret `es-http-tls` (has `tls.crt`, `tls.key`, `ca.crt`)\n2. Use the existing password secret `elastic-password` with key `password`\n3. Deploy a 3-node StatefulSet with the Elasticsearch 8.11.1 image\n4. Create a headless service for pod discovery (es-transport or es-nodes)\n5. Set up an `es-http` service for external and internal access on port 9200 with TLS enabled\n\nFor Elasticsearch 8.11.1, I need to enable security settings in the configuration: security must be turned on, HTTPS needs to be configured for client connections, and inter-node communication also requires TLS. Since I only have the `es-http-tls` certificate available, I'll use it for both HTTP and transport layer encryption.\n\nNow I'm planning the core components: a ConfigMap for the elasticsearch.yml settings, a StatefulSet with three replicas for the cluster, a headless Service to handle pod discovery on the transport port, and the ClusterIP Service for client access. For the configuration file, I need to set the cluster name, derive the node name from the pod hostname, bind to all interfaces, and configure the discovery mechanism.\n\nConfiguring TLS and security settings... - elasticsearch-2\n\nSo the initial master nodes list will be those three pod names. I'll name the StatefulSet `elasticsearch` to keep it straightforward.\n\nFor the node name, I can use the pod's metadata name directly through a fieldRef, which gives me the pod name as the node identifier. I'll set up two services: a headless service called `es-nodes` for inter-node communication on port 9300, and a regular service `es-http` for client access on port 9200. Now I need to think through the storage configuration for this test setup.\n\nSince the goal is just to verify read/write connectivity, I'll use `emptyDir` volumes to avoid dealing with PVC provisioning and storage classes. This keeps things simple and lets the pods start quickly. I should also account for the `vm.max_map_count` kernel parameter that Elasticsearch 8.x requires, though it might already be set on the host. Let me start writing out the manifests with these decisions in place.\n\nFor the Elasticsearch configuration, I'm setting up the cluster with security enabled and using the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable from a secret to initialize the elastic user's password on first startup. Writing the ConfigMap and Secret definitions... Writing Kubernetes manifests... Configuring the volume mounts and resource limits for the Elasticsearch container, then setting up the volumes themselves with a ConfigMap for configuration, a Secret for TLS certificates, and an empty directory for data storage. I'm reconsidering how environment variables work in ES 8.x—the dotted notation like `node.name` should be picked up directly, though I need to verify the exact override mechanism for elasticsearch.yml settings. In ES 8.x, environment variables follow the convention of replacing dots with underscores and uppercasing the setting name, though there can be naming conflicts. Rather than wrestling with environment variable conventions, I could set the node name directly in the elasticsearch.yml config file, but since each pod needs a unique name based on its hostname, I'd need to generate or override the config at startup time.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is to let Elasticsearch default to using the pod's hostname as the node name—so I won't set `node.name` in the ConfigMap at all. Then I just need to configure `cluster.initial_master_nodes` with the expected node names like `[\"elasticsearch-0\", \"elasticsearch-1\", \"elasticsearch-2\"]`. I'll skip the PodDisruptionBudget since it's not explicitly required. For TLS, ES 8.x enables it by default for both HTTP and transport layers using the pre-existing secret, but since transport TLS between nodes needs valid certificates for pod DNS names, I'll set the verification mode to certificate-only to avoid hostname verification issues.\n\nFor the HTTP endpoint, clients connect through the `es-http` service so the certificate should be valid for that. I'm planning to mount just the elasticsearch.yml file via ConfigMap subPath rather than replacing the entire config directory, which preserves the image's default configuration files like jvm.options and log4j2.properties.\n\nI need to account for `cluster.initial_master_nodes` which should reference the actual pod hostnames (elasticsearch-0, elasticsearch-1, elasticsearch-2), and I should include a privileged init container to set `vm.max_map_count` since Elasticsearch requires it, though this might fail depending on the cluster's security policies.\n\nWriting the complete manifest...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":290,"cache_read_input_tokens":28733,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":290},"output_tokens":13,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"341d3ee3-65cf-4814-807b-64d19a8dd616","uuid":"30244b3e-c81b-4422-9dd7-b7082d1bb11e","request_id":"req_011Cc82eyGEYfiabp4t76CPR"}
